I cannot write to `.claude/settings.json` or edit `.claude/settings.local.json` without user approval — the project settings files themselves require a permission grant to modify.

**What to add to `.claude/settings.local.json`** (already exists, just needs updating):

```json
{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash(unzip *)",
      "Bash(make firered)",
      "Bash(make check)",
      "Bash(make clean)",
      "Bash(make firered *)",
      "Bash(/opt/devkitpro/devkitARM/bin/arm-none-eabi-gcc *)"
    ]
  }
}
```

**What I skipped and why:**
- `ls`, `cat`, `head`, `tail`, `wc`, `find`, `grep`, `which`, `file`, `sha1sum`, `git log/show/diff/status`, `echo`, `printf` — all **auto-allowed**, no entry needed
- `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`, `git tag` — **write/mutate** operations; not appropriate for read-only allowlist (need separate approval)
- `make *` (wildcard) — too broad, grants arbitrary code execution via make recipes
- `python3 *` — arbitrary code execution, must not be wildcarded

The only commands that actually require a permission grant for this build session are:
1. `make firered` (the ROM build)
2. `git add -A && git commit` (committing progress) — these are already auto-approved by the automation script's `--permission-mode auto`

The root issue: this appears to be an **interactive session**, not an automation session. In automation mode (`--permission-mode auto`), all these would be approved without prompts. The user should run via `.automation/run-session.sh` for fully autonomous operation.
